<user_name>m parra<//user_name><Time>1590639775212</Time><rate>1<//rate>< review>
Very bad service. I asked for a mocha with microphone milk but instead I got a cold mocha with flat milk. I had to asked them to remake the mocha again and to make sure that they make it with microphone milk but again I got it with the flat milk and this time it was very hot that I burned my mouth. I had to wait for a long time for the mocha to be able to drink it. Also, my wife had a green tea macha with cinnamon flavor, so I had to call back to explain the bad experience. The woman who answered the telephone was rude. When I was explaining about the green tea she didnt answer the phone anymore. I had to walk back to peet's store and asked for the manager but there was only a supervisor. Also, my wife drank the green tea matcha with lots of ice. Tylor, the supervisor who took the order knew my wife asked for a green tea matcha with little ice but she remake it with lots of ice. I told her that we didn't get what we asked for and instead of trying to find out what happened she became aggressive and responded by saying, " I have been working for 10 years, dude" my name is not dude. If I go to peet's coffee and not 7-11 is because they know how to prepare a good cup of coffee. She was mad that I asked for the right drinks. After all I paid for good coffee and I have the right to get it. She has not right to decide how my wife and me drink the coffee. If she doesn't like to provide good service she shouldn't be working at peet's coffee. For many years I have been coming to this location because I like their good service and coffee. But today wasn't good service and coffee.< /review>

<UserId.>102075195216525523515</UserId.>< Name>
Sean Schluntz<//Name>
< time>
1456548567309</time>
<rate>5<//rate>< review>
I generally like Peet's and it is my favorite coffee chain. This location can be a bit hard to get to, rarely has open places to sit, and often has a line, a week ago something happened that really rocketed it up in my opinion as a business.

So many places are so tied to technology that they can't function without it. I've been turned away from places that can't do any business if the computer doesn't work, or will only take cash when the register is down. It drives me nuts, basic math for making change and filling out a paper credit card slip is easy.

So, how does that relate to Peet's? Well two weeks ago I went in early on a Sunday to get my usual cappuccino and a thermos of coffee for my pop who was working at the Good Guys car show. I arrived to find the line all the way to the far door, not a great sign but I'll wait in the line here rather than going to the drive-through coffee hut across 580. The computers were down and this was slowing the service, but they were doing great even with the delays.

One person was walking the line and taking orders on a sticky pad and then running them up to the barista so the drinks would keep flowing.  Each of the register locations had a staffer taking payment, and they even still took credit cards using the old manual swipe machines. The staff were upbeat (if a bit frazzled) but business continued.  I can't think of many places that would have handled the situation as well as the team did at this location, and they could be commended for it.< /review>

<Rate>3</Rate><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Review>
i was a little disappointed by this ice cream spot after reading the reviews about exotic flavors. most flavors are generic- chocolate varieties, cheesecake of some sort, vanillas, your typical ice cream flavors which were just ok. they had four exotic flavors consisting of rosewater when i visited- which were great (only because i love flowery tasting ice cream in general) i got the orange blossom ice cream (a flowery ice cream not fruity) which was better in a mashti sandwich. my bf got the rosewater saffron which was also good. however, for the drive and destination location, i can't say their flowery ice cream (nor their normal flavors) even compares to some other i've had at ici, bi-rite or even carmela's. it's also on the pricey side given atmosphere and portions. i wouldn't go back given the other choices in the city.< /Review>

<name>Cerulean Fish</name>< review>
Walked in 1st visit. Small frontage order area, register to the right small bit of counter seating to the left. Kind of like a Creamisry with fresher ingredients. The concept is to use top notch ingredients and create ice cream using the nitrogen process. It's an old chemistry class trick that when done right using their custom machines, makes very smooth ice cream. Ok, regarding the smoothness, straight up I'd be back in a heartbeat for the product. As for price the website looks like no update since March 2018 (?) We were able to order the Lil Bites (?) maybe used to be Lil Scientists. This is a limited menu of smaller sized, but less expensive choices @ 4.50$/ea. This choice was a value and as a dinner dessert plenty for portion size. A few downsides... We ordered thinking we were first to be served. With only two ice cream machines in use, there were actually two orders ahead of us. We didn't want to seem impatient, but our order was ready 20+ minutes after ring up. Be cautious if you are going to a movie, etc. There was what looked like three young staff and one Supervisor/Mgr on shift to make orders. With orders coming in I did not see the machine bowls filled, churning out ice cream. I have no clue what wait time is when they have a rush but I'm sure it's more than 20+ minutes. There was the usual pop music medium volume in the store. Hip n cool, yes, but bummer the staff was shouting over the combo of music and the air blasts the nitrogen made as it hit the mixing bowl. I didn't care to much for one employee discussing work hours and employee habits while making the ice cream. As first time customers, I thought the register/counter person could have been more helpful or friendly to us. The girl at the "finishing" station was moving a bit slow compared to back service restuarant people I've worked with. Again as commented only one machine of two was used on average, sometimes two. Magically, they did get orders out in a roughly smooth operation. There was a looseness to the group for example a woman came in and just waited at the register for service for quite some time before being noticed. The place was very clean as expected. A little bit of old ice cream and toppings floating in the dipper wells. I did notice an employee rinsing blades in the dipper wells instead of being sanitized in the sink. Overall an average experience with very good ice cream. I can see this is a good product by people with good intentions. FYI, I've managed and sold ice cream, not easy. My intent here is not to anonymously rip on a store. I hope they resolve the output issue to make more product faster but still keep quality. Also, I know it's a challenge to manage kids getting minimum wage, but they owe the company to represent the product and encourage people to come back. Leasing at Fashion Island is not cheap. Oh and its AUG 2018, keeping websites current is extra work on top of 14 hour days, I know I've worked them. But current info sells the awesome fresh ingredient model to a wider group of people for you... Thank you kindly for the great ice cream tonight.<//review>

< Review>
Pretty low quality service and at best it has lukewarm amateur tacos. Make sure to go here if you feel like getting made fun of for asking what's in the tacos (with the nationality card, no less) by someone who is the exact same nationality yet refuses to speak your language and speaks with an accent stronger than most first gens'. So yeah, pleasant place; it just screams hospitality. Gave it 2 stars since the register guy seemed pretty nice, though. On the food side the tacos aren't terrible but could be better. The quality won't get any better since there's no competition though  So in short, the tacos and the people are best enjoyed the same: faaaaar away from you.<//Review>

<Review>Friday, Saturday and Sunday this tiny market & deli has the best street tacos around!! Old school little corn tortillas with the best carne asada,  carnitas, chicken and barbacoa meats grilled right in front of you on the patio! Nothing fancy, just fresh cilantro and onions.  So freaking good! They also have burritos and quesadillas with whatever meat you want. Also everyday they serve up some  pretty amazing sandwiches in the little deli. Fresh breads, meats, cheeses, and veggies! VERY friendly staff,  nice and clean,  so grab some tacos  (4, one of each) and a cold beer! No, really,  go there!<//Review><pictures>None<//pictures>< response>

< Rate>

<Name>Dee U</Name><text>it is with a heavy heart that I write this review. I previously posted a 5 star review at the urging of my attorneys "PR/Media" gal. I complied as the firm had become a sponsor of a Heart Association event my daughter and I spearheaded in Beverly Hills. This sponsorship was in lieu of me giving them a positive review. I have since deleted it and am updating my rating and review.

It's simple. My life was ruined and I lost everything material after a woman raced through a stop sign and t-boned my daughter and myself, pushing us into a parked SUV.

I was referred to CZR by my original attorney, stating the case was "TOO BIG" for him. I met with Steve Mazza initially who asked me if they took my case, would I be willing to get the surgery that was recommended by my Doctors. I answered that I would, of course. (I am missing a piece of vertebrae between my C-5 & C-6).

In addition, I suffered from a 7 mil bulge/protrusion which I received numerous epidurals as treatment, which provided only temporary relief. My income of 80-90,000 was jeopardized as I was an internet entrepreneur and could no longer sit at the computer. I had an amazing business and life. A single Mom, while I worked many hours but my business afforded me the luxury of a flexible schedule so I could keep close eye on my teenaged daughter. All this changed following this accident.

I was forced (under duress) and almost 2 years of extreme pressure to accept a settlement. By the time medical bills were paid and Carpenter, Zuckerman and Rowley received their money, there was no money left to get the surgery that I desperately needed and had agreed to get. We were six figures short! Big swing. I am faced with debilitating pain every day. I am unable to work and definitely NOT the same woman I was prior to this accident. I have been struggling ever since and it has adversely affected my daughters life. She too suffers from extreme back pain and is now only 21. She has a long life ahead of her, I only hope she doesn't experience the pain I deal with regularly.

I provided CZR with every document they needed, income etc. My daughter and I lost our residence and my source of income. With few options I was forced to live in a shelter in the desert and my daughter was forced to live with friends so she could finish her last year of high school. Separated from my baby, the stress was too much from all of this and I had heart failure. Subsequently, I was forced to have heart surgery. I would call this "cause & effect". I was born with a heart defect and the stress caused by this accident and the events that followed were all a huge factor in regards to my condition.

Bottom line... my experience was that they did not have my families best interest at heart. All they cared about was lining their own pockets.

On a personal note, I don't know him well but Nick Rowley is trouble. My daughter was considering law school and took a part time job with CZR as a "law file clerk" for a few months. She is a GOOD girl, excellent student, peer counselor at her high school, helped me raise $15,000 for the American Heart Association and is big on civic duty.  She was seeking sponsorship for an event and reached out to the attorneys for sponsorship. Nick Rowley emailed her and said he had feelings for her and wanted to fly her off somewhere "exotic" and take care of her. As handsome, charming and as rich as the man is... my daughter returned an email respectfully declining. Our attorney (Candice) told her to stay far away from him, as he had impregnated several women and cheated on his wife (whom he had also impregnated!) My daughter heeded Candice's advice. This behavior was completely inappropriate and the firm is unethical.

Also, they old my daughter that they would NOT take their fee out of her (very small) settlement. They did. They really dropped the ball. Beware!</text>< UserId.>
110299149103157393188< /UserId.>

This is an awesome service to the community!
They have a little room off to the side, where we've had small meetings.
The nice thing is that they offer really good bobba teas, and some snackie items, and the girls in the meeting really enjoy coming here.
It's centrally located near the Boulevard, and not far from the high school. And it's adjacent to Castro Village.
The owner is super sweet, and I have only kind things to say about them.
Please support them, because it's a mom and pop shop located here in town, and any place like that should be supported.  But, best of all they serve yummy stuff!< /text>

< review>
I've been looking for "The Killing Joke" by Alan Moore for a while now, and had seen it in a used bookstore down in LA, but didn't get it. So I'm really happy when on my first visit, I saw that Comic Grapevine carries the novel. Score! The store is kind of hidden, so you may have to look carefully to know when to make the turn into the plaza (I had to make a u-turn because I missed it lol). It's located in an unassuming area. The owner of the store is very kind. He sparked conversation with me about the book. I don't know much about the Batman novel series, so I just nodded and agreedüòÖ. I also purchased two Pok√©mon booster packs for my little sister, and the owner gave a complementary poster for her as well. It was a really nice surprise and gesture! I will be back for more graphic novels :D In addition to superhero graphic novels, the store also carries manga, figurines, and more small knickknacks.<//review>

1607815462177<//Date>
<Rate>3</Rate>< review>
This place is definitely not as good as the reviews.  If this weren't in Cloverdale it would be 2 stars.  The people are very nice, but that doesn't make the food any better..

The sushi is ok, good enough for when I have a craving.  I don't know what they think a 49er roll is though, check out any restaurant in the bay area, it's salmon and avocado with a thinly sliced lemon on top.  There are some weird Americanized rolls here, I've only had the classic maki and the spicy scallop hand roll.  I do appreciate that the california roll is made with real crab and that they don't use MSG.

The Asian food however is really bad.  The meats are low quality and spongy textured, not browned at all, and there isn't much flavor is anything I've had so far.  I've had the wonton soup, chow mein with pork, and tom kha with chicken.  The wonton soup was ok, dough was definitely on the thick and gluey side and it needed more broth/why are there pho noodles in it?  I think I just really wanted some Asian soup that day though.  The chow mein and tom kha were really disappointing, I wound up throwing away the remainder.  The tom kha was strange tasting, the best thing in it was the mushrooms and those were also low quality.  I wound up not eating the meat in either the noodle dish or tom kha.  Chow mein was bland, oily and the noodles were soft/gluey instead of chewy and slightly browned.

Bottom line is I'd order the sushi if I really wanted some sushi, but no matter the cravings I'm done trying things on the other section of their menu.< /review>

Plus we do not want you to get home and find your won ton dough and meat are separate as you are about to enjoy them! 5</Rate>
<text>What can I say about Pacific Edge that hasn't already been said?
This is the end-all, be-all of the human climbing experience.
Hundreds of square feet of towering, inviting walls with some of the best-set routes in the game. Front desk staff? Try and beat 'em. This is the warmest, most welcoming gym I've ever been to. If you're struggling with a route, ask someone behind the counter for a beta and they'll be inexhaustibly stoked to help you out.
Routes are (allegedly) set a little harder than at other gyms, but who ever said sending should be a cakewalk? The weight room is smallish, but totally adequate and never super crowded. Bathrooms are always clean, and the sauna cranks.< /text>< user_name>
Joey< /user_name>

<time>1549262545028<//time><username>C B</username><Gmap_id>0x808e6aa5192dca37:0xd208c0335d7129ef<//Gmap_id><response>None</response><UserId.>104732196008016991605< /UserId.><Rate>2< /Rate>< pictures>

< review>
Went climbing here with some friends(3 of us total, all first timers to this gym, but not to climbing). We all left rather disappointed with our experience. So this review is primarily for their bouldering area as we didn't feel like going through the belay test.

Anyway, I was unfortunate enough to have to rent shoes as I had left my gear at home, the rental shoes are comfortable but not sticky at all. Combine this with the dirty and worn out footholds and you've got next to no footing on quite a few of the routes I tried(ranges from V0 to V3), where I did find footing, I found awkward routesetting and crummy hand holds. Almost everything felt caked in ages of shoe rubber, chalk, and climber. That said, a couple routes I tried were fun and a neat change from my usual gyms, but the overall experience left a lot to be desired. I called it a day after an hour and a half of frustration while my friends lasted a bit longer. Maybe having their own gear helped?

All said and done, the facility was well lit and generally clean and the couple of staff members I interacted with were friendly, but we all agreed, we are in no rush at all to go back there.

Also note: the people saying this is "the best rock gym in Santa Cruz"... It's the ONLY rock gym in Santa Cruz, unless there's one at UCSC that I don't think most of us have access to.<//review>

<user_name>Dionne Obeso</user_name><date>1465427544464<//date><rate>5< /rate>< text>
This is an excellent gym run by climbers with experience and "cred". The problems are a lot harder than others with the same ranking at other Bay Area gyms, making them closer to outdoor climbing ratings. Just don't be surprised if you climb 5.11s at Planet Granite and find yourself knocked bank to 10s at PE.

They also offer periphery services like a decent pro shop, climbing lessons, yoga, and fitness equipment.< /text>

< Review>
This is THE PLACE TO BE. Diverse walls that are constantly being reset with titillating new routes, staff that are always helpful and never dull, clean facilities that can accommodate any need you have, and it's actually affordable.

Do you want 100 different weight lifting machines, an espresso/smoothie bar, a full sauna and member lounge, and exclusive 1:1 yoga sessions with a level 9000+ yogi with their pineal gland fully decalcified!?!?!?!?!

Well go fist yourself, because you're the one ruining indoor climbing facilities with your absurd demands.

This place is everything you need in a climbing facility, and nothing more.<//Review>

< Text>
Great environment. Very friendly staff. Most of the top rope routes are 5.8 and above. The routes are creative and challenging. They have tall walls, short walls, overhanging walls (in the lead climbing area), a slab, a chimney, and two bouldering areas. People of all ages climb here: kids, teens, 20/30-somthing, and older adults. It's a little pricy, but what climbing gym isn't? Also, last Friday of each month, women get a discount on a day pass.</Text>

<rate>5</rate>< Review>
How can you not love this place? Sure it's not as big as PG, but that means you don't have to deal with all the bad aspects of the mega gyms (prices, crowds, etc.). The staff are all friendly, VERY knowledgeable, and I haven't been to another gyms where 80% of the people climb outside as well! Definitely recommend if you want to get into climbing, or are looking to train to climb harder.</Review>

<rate>4<//rate>< Review>
Worthwhile investment if the card includes a number of attractions you intend to do individually. The card then opens up a bunch of extra attractions that you might not have considered, but now you can do for no extra cost! Handy to jump queues. The iPhone app was easy to use.

Card use restricted to 9am-5.30pm, not the actual opening hours of the attractions which is odd and limiting. I would suggest a lower cost of the card due to that. Have previously used the New York version of this card and it doesn't have this weird time restriction.<//Review>

The bus advertising wrap prevents the downstairs windows from opening, so there's only a small window for air circulation. This wrap has no holes in it so it is completely opaque. You can see nothing except what is visible thru the front windshield. <userid>118059990205818170220<//userid>< username>
Dillon Mysliwiec</username>
<Review>Los Angeles is great, however, the traffic can be very time consuming (let alone frustrating). Due to the time limit of 5:30PM access on the card, it makes it difficult to explore the city. At least twice, I went over the time due to an accident on the highway on my way to an attraction. This made the trip more frustrating than pleasurable.

For reference, I grabbed the 5 day pass, therefore to make the card worth the money, I had to go to many attractions. In hind-sight, too many days on the card makes for a hectic and unenjoyable experience. My best experiences in the city were the events I went to not included on the Go City Card.

If you go for a week. Plan your routes extensively including delays due to traffic and you'll have a less stressful time than I had. Also, I wouldn't go any higher than a 3 day pass so you can spend time just enjoying the city rather than trying to make your money back.

If used properly, it can save you money, but be very aware of the travel time and that 5:30PM time limit. Also, check the prices fo the attractions you plan to see to see if the card is even worth it. Many of the attractions included on the card are very inexpensive.</Review><Pictures>None< /Pictures></record></dataset><record>

<Review>We purchased (5) 3 day cards.

Day 1 - Universal Studios
Day 2 - Aquarium of the Pacific and Queen Mary
Day 3 - WB Tour and Los Angeles Zoo

I gave the Go City LA card 3 stars.

Pros - saved some money on admission and gave us ideas of what to do while in LA.  Helped with budgeting, as we were able to figure out a basic itinerary and pay ahead by buying the cards.

Cons - 5:30 cutoff time made it so we were not able to fit in as much as we wanted. We ended up paying for activities that were included on the card because we just weren't able to make it there before 5:30.
You must plan activities and drive time ahead, to get the most out of each card.

After figuring out the cost of the cards and the admission prices, we basically got one admission free on the 3 day card - per person.</Review><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< response>

< text>
I bought the 3 day pass for me and my daughter to use while in the LA area. We had 1 1/2 days in Hollywood before we were leaving on a cruise and another day when we returned. The pass allowed us to use the three days within 2 week period, so it was perfect for us. We Went to Warner Brothers, Universal, Madame Tussauds, Hollywood Theater, and TCL Chinese Theatre. It more than paid for itself. We would have done more if we had more time. The main complaint I have is the Hop On Hop Off bus is for the Yellow Route only, Santa Monica area only. It was useless, and we were planning to use this to get from one location to another. Big surprise and disappointment. LYFT saved us but was an unexpected expense.< /text>

<rating>5< /rating><review>My family had an amazing trip experience. We were able to go to 7 different attractions from the available package deal. We went to LEGOLAND on the first day; the Aquarium Of The Pacific, K1 Go Cart, and Santa Monica Pier the second day; Universal Studios on the third day; and then Knott's Berry Farm and Knott's Soak City on the forth day. The whole trip was definitely a great a great experience, we took lots of pictures, got tons of little souvenirs, the app for the Go Card worked perfectly for information and mapping everything out. We printed our passes just in case there was an issue with the app since I had read was a possible issue for some people, but everything was a great trip and a much needed vacation. All the parks had souvenir drinks that could be filled up for free all day so that helped with the heat and the humidity during August, the food was a little expensive but local restaurants and fast food were not too far for us to stop at instead. We did have a very tiny issue with our cell phones loosing charge extremely fast while in California, living in Arizona a normal 100% charge will last me more than a single day here even with using my phone often, but while in California a single charge would last maybe 6-8 hrs at the most and most places don't have public charging areas, or ones that were not obvious to find. I recommend bringing a camera for all photos instead of using a cell phone. Overall my family had a great trip and wish we could of stayed longer, but had to head home and back to work.< /review>< pics>

< UserId.>
112251595599656210376<//UserId.>
< Name>
Louise Barakat< /Name>
<Time>1503252572154< /Time>< rate>
4<//rate>
< Review>
Used for Day 1: Universal (crowded! rides are short for loooong waits 45-70mins) but the park is set up nicely and enjoyed the setting; saw Mario Lopez taping live, Day 2: 6-Flags (highly recommended for ride folks - world's first 4-dimensional coasters, no lines (15 mins max on most popular rides) and the rides can last 3.5 minutes (of terror in some cases!) mid-week, late July, and Day 3: midday Long Beach Whale Watch cruise (saw dolphins only but tour saw whales day before.  Larger boat was clean and enjoyable, big waves did cause a few of us to be slightly nauseous, just depends on your sea legs!).  We also took in the Aquarium next door and petting sharks and manta rays of various sizes which was highly addictive! (validated 1/2 price $8 vs $16 parking showing parking pass to either Aquarium of Boat Desk).  Not enough time to take in Queen Mary on the other side, closeby, before (4:30 entry time on pass I heard, not confirmed even though 5:30PM is last entry time for most venues).  There's a shuttle bus from Aquarium to Qn Mary if you have time.  I would suggest taking the earliest cruise,  8 or 9AM as it's 3 hrs long, then the Aquarium and over to Qn Mary that stays open until 10PM or so as you get one free tour with pass.  Other areas are accessible without additional cost, like the cocktail bar and restaurant to enjoy sunset.

Also since 6 Flags is so amazing for it's rides and ease of getting around, but not so huge that you can't go back and fore to rides, although makes sense to start at back of park and work forward; I would suggest doing Universal Studios before 6 Flags experience because the rides are so phenomenal you won't be disappointed (as we were) with the long waits for short rides at Universal having attending 6-Flags before.  Get your thrill ride experiences at 6-Flags and be rewarded with the longer more intense rides there.  I didn't find it any quicker to pre-buy my $20 parking pass online for 6-Flags either as there was no signed for pre-bought passes to get through line (could be wrong) and it costs a few $ more to process online vs charging it while there going through booth.

Pass is Easy to use once you have correct information!  I began panicking that we had to use the 3-Day pass in 3 consecutive days.  That is incorrect, as you have 3 days within 2 wks to use the pass in LA. I called CSvc and was misinformed by agent that it was indeed 3 consecutive days and since we were about to use the passes it meant re-arranging schedules to accommodate since we were planning to space activities out.  I even asked to speak to a supervisor to re-clarify the information, took my # since they were unavailable at time and never received a phone call back.  I tried calling again the next day and was re-assured this time by the agent and he checked the City location to make sure; LA is not a city requiring 3 days consecutive use -- of course makes since given it's span of valid locations and traffic, but sometimes good deals seem to be just that, too good a deal to be true.

We bought 14 passes on a group rate and they are refundable within a year if not used.  I would recommend these passes, but plan ahead to fit in as much as you can in a day.  One Caveat: sometimes there are online passes for mid-week that are cheap, like $38 for 6-Flags so account for possibly paying out of pocket for those passes and use Go-Pass for more expensive, non-discounted entries.  Forgot to look at the small print and we shopped like fiends at The Citadel luxury outlets and there was an additional coupon book we could of got had we shown our passes at the office.  Next time!< /Review>

<user_name>Stephen Woerner<//user_name>< Gmap_id>
0x80d954a537cf6609:0x7ce3aab649fad79e</Gmap_id>
<userid>112322280621053976456<//userid><Response>None<//Response><pics>None</pics><rate>3</rate>< Review>
This place is small space-wise, menu-wise, and TV wise. I'm kind of confused about what they're going for.

The space isn't that big a deal. The menu only offers 4 burgers, and 2 kinds of fries. They do offer blackbean burgers as option. The kitchen staff is quick and the food we did get was delicious.

More disappointing is that their beer selection is tiny! There is only 4 beers on tap, but each beer well selected. They have a similarly small wine selection. And a decent liquor selection.

There were a good number of people  watching the Stanley Cup hockey game, but the TVs were small. The space had some interesting atmosphere, but a lot of blank dark painted walls too.

So honestly, I don't know what this place is going for and I'm not sure they know either. I enjoyed my burger, fries, and beer but I feel like I've seen everything this place has to offer after one visit. Maybe I'd go back if it were cheaper but they charge brewery prices for to little in my opinion. Its worth a try if you've never been

Edit: A lot of people are saying this place has the best burger in town. Not even close. Burgers are 7/10 at best. The bar in SD is high< /Review>

<name>Alexis Hernandez< /name><time>1556508855834<//time><rate>5< /rate><review>This is a must try in San Diego! The portion size is average which is great if you are trying to fill your burger needs. I ordered a Balboa Burger and the California Burgito . The Balboa has a great taste, the beef is very juicy and high quality. The tomatoes and lettuce are very crisp, topped of with soft buns and fresh aioili house sauce. The Kennebec fries are great since they have little bit of spice. It was a very original take on burgers and it exceeded my expectations. The location its self is a hole in the wall but it definitely shines when being introduced to the traditional bar decor. Kevin the person helping us out was very professional and on top of it. I would recommend to come early on the weekdays because I could totally see this place being very popular on the weekends. Overall I would highly recommend The Balboa... Pro tip everyday from 4-6pm The Balboa burger is $5. What a steal. Hope they keep this promotion.<//review>< pics>

< user>
117030317423620717440< /user>
< user_name>
Todd Clemmons</user_name>
<date>1579969810603< /date><Rating>5</Rating>< review>
Hole in the wall dive bar with one heck of a good burger!
Heard about this place from many friends who believe The Balboa has one of, if not the, best burgers in San Diego.
After trying many other spots (Hodads, Rocky's, The Friendly, etc.), I can truly say that they do indeed make my Top 10 list. Only reason they didn't make the Top 5 was that I don't put anyone in the Top 5 unless I've tried their burger multiple times.
The burger is flat-top grill cooked, served on a soft fresh traditional bun with lettuce, tomato, onions, cheese and their secret zesty aioli sauce.
DON'T expect a super clean restaurant style  place, this is a transitional dive bar and keeps it real.<//review>

<user_name>Dhanashree Adhikari</user_name>< Rating>

< UserId.>
113699882208050664373</UserId.>
<Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM6ptMza3h12jZUT9MBdJBK4-c26gJnMrnmiJdX=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics><resp>None</resp><review>What an amazing spot! I am not surprised that its a local favorite. I did not try any other burger joints in SD, but this is by far the best burger I have had. Although I have to be honest I haven't had many.

The place is in a very quiet neighborhood, it was very close to our airbnb. It doesn't look like much from the outside but its what inside that matters - burgers!!! We went on a Monday night and there where still people there. Its quite dimly lit, have about 5-6 tables and bar seating.

Now about the food. The burgers are amazing!! Me and my husband both had their balboa burger and it was just perfect! The patty was dripping! I was using the wrap they give with the burger and still ended up with juices on my hands. The bun is perfectly toasted and adds a charred flavor to the burger. The toppings are simple some onions, tomatoes and their sauce which is bomb! We both inhaled our burgers. The drinks were really nice too. I got their cucumber punch and it was really refreshing, nice break from the meaty burger. We got garlic fries on the side and these were one of the most well seasoned fries I have had in a restaurant. So good!! Service was quick and easy.

Would highly recommend to all meat-lovers. Also tip: you can get an extra patty if you are extra hungry.</review><time>1570637906090<//time><GmapID>0x80d954a537cf6609:0x7ce3aab649fad79e</GmapID></record>

<user_name>Jay Keyes</user_name>< gmapID>
0x80d954a537cf6609:0x7ce3aab649fad79e<//gmapID>
<Text>Balboa Bar & Grill is a dive bar that serves the best burgers in San Diego, bar none. Everything about Balboa Bar & Grill's's burgers, including the beef mixture ratio, the secret garlic aioli recipe, and even their brand of mustard, has been purposefully and uniquely chosen to deliver a transcendent and congruent burger experience where the whole is much greater than the mere sum of its parts, but the most impressive unique feature are their buns, which are freshly-baked bolillo rolls shaped like hamburger buns. Some San Diegans may recognize bolillo as the same French-lilke Mexican bread used to make molettes and tortas in households and restaurants around the region.

And, yes, the other reviews you'll read about the delicious garlic fries are on point -- but I usually find myself ordering the regular fries made of the same Kennebec potatoes which are just as nice and crispy, but allow me to actually open my mouth around other people later in the evening without melting their faces.

In short, this is THE place to get burgers in San Diego.<//Text><user_id>108685370139018629938< /user_id><Rate>5</Rate>< Pics>

1447727524705<//Date>

< Text>
Burgers are a very important thing to me and great ones can be difficult to find in fat phobic Southern California.  The Balboa has taken the burger to a zen level of mastery, great quality beef cooked on a nice heavy grill, hot enough to make that wonderful, but elusive, crust on the outside without destroying the inside.  The buns are fresh, custom made and delicious.  Overall I believe these are the BEST BURGERS in San Diego.  The garlic fries were a little intense for my taste buds but they are unique and I recommend giving them a try.

A nice selection of beers and a few other menu items round out the overall excellent experience.<//Text>

The burgers here are so legit, that I kindly ask you never to come here. Their menu is no frills and all deliciousness. It's a small place and as such, it is sometimes hard to find a table. <text>I am not very familiar with downtown San Diego. From the surface and not knowing any better, this doesn't seem like a part of town you want to hang around, especially once the sun goes down. The Balboa is small. There is a bar with probably a dozen-ish stools and then maybe 8 dinning tables. I could be off by 1 or 2 in my count. Anyways, the service was great and the bartender was very friendly. The Balboa Burger was excellent, I highly recommend and I would happily eat it again. The Garlic Fries, not so much. They weren't terrible but they weren't good. I guess I would use the word eatable to describe them. The place is very dark. When you enter during daylight, you will need a few minutes for your eyes to adjust so you can see. I felt like the pricing was very fair for what I received. No table side service, you need to order at the bar counter. This is not really a family place. So maybe leave the kids home. I would go back and I would recommend.</text><GmapID>0x80d954a537cf6609:0x7ce3aab649fad79e< /GmapID><user_id>107711030070372794261< /user_id></record>

< Review>
Bad customer service & terrible workers!
I typically do not have energy for negativity but this place really did it. It was date night last Friday. I came in after a long day to enjoy a delicious burger. I came in thinking my night was going to be enjoyable but the workers made sure I did not have a good evening. We walked in and saw a small spot where we can eat. I said Hello then began to order food. The worker rudely interrupted my order and asked to see ID. Okay we showed him our ID's. Then he said there is no room to sit. I had to show him that there was seats. He then proceeded and took our order. Once we sat down there was a worker who brought us the burgers and then when I asked him for a water he refused and said I need to go to the bar to get a water. I got in line again at the bar waited several minutes before being helped while my food is getting cold. Then I order my water. The bartender went to pour my water then someone interrupted him and asked for water he gave them my water instead. leaving me to wait once again. They did not say anything nice. no greetings no anything. They seem to really hate it there. Not sure why. But they need to treat the customers with some courtesy and respect. They work with people. Either hire a more lively group of workers or train them. This is not okay. I am an organizer for the San Diego community and I will not refer any friends or bring groups of people here to support this business. Do not come here.</Review>

<time>1406482609389< /time><Rating>4<//Rating><Review>So I've been to Tin Can Ale House a handful of times as a performer and spectator and never had the 'pleasure' of having a Dood Food burger. < name>
Douglas LeClair<//name>
< text>
It seems they no longer offer a happy hour :(

If you check the Google reviews of this restaurant, you'll notice that "happy hour" the top keyword mentioned and probably weighs heavily into the older ratings.

I'm kind of torn because I was on an emotional roller coaster watching Balboa's original location almost close, then come back even bigger. I called and they said they've done away with their happy hour menu which is kind of disappointing because their regular prices have gone up a fair amount.

I understand the pandemic situation and that restaurants have struggled this past last year, but it seems like a lot of places are too good to offer any kind of incentives to loyal regular customers anymore.

The burgers are great for purists who don't want a sauced-up, condiment-laden burger that hides the quality of the meat. Are they worth regular menu price? For me, I don't know -- I want to support the Balboa but now it seems an out-of-reach luxury I might have to regrettably pass on in the future.<//text>
